        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>Jan. 18/56</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>New York</placeName>    <placeName>144 Amos
                    St.</placeName>    <placeName>Hudson St.</placeName></p>
            <p>Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Although I have (only yesterday) learned that you<lb/> cannot
                conveniently attend to any communication for your next number if<lb/> not sent in by
                the <date>10<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> yet since “where there's a will there is a
                way” I may<lb/> perhaps yet be in time. Last month I have ventured to address you on
                the<lb/> subject of my Grammar, but am now in doubt whether it has reached you,<lb/>
                finding that I had misdirected it. In it I stated my intention to (as I am<lb/>
                persuaded to do) send about circulars with the view of obtaining subsc<lb/>ribers to
                the work, and was only waiting to be able to refer to some<lb/> testimonial from
                parties known to be competent judges. I am<lb/> fully aware you not having seen the
                work cannot but deter you from<lb/> saying any thing about it, but I think if you
                are inclined to favor one<lb/> you could do so by acquainting the public with the
                opinion of <persName>Drs Raphall</persName><lb/> &amp; <persName>Benisch</persName>
                on the merits of the said book. The latter gentleman spontaneously<lb/> offered to
                do all he could to forward my object; and accordingly you will find<lb/> in No. 99
                of the Hebrew Observer Nos. 24. <date>1854</date> Pages 585. &amp; 590. how far
                he<lb/> has redeemed his pledge, and that, without any remuneration, he has
                repeated<lb/> in the columns of his succeeding numbers more than a dozen times; by
                means<lb/> of which the copyright together with the whole impression of the last
                edition<lb/> was greedily bought up, so that I have not left a copy of it to present
                you with,<lb/> or even one for my own use, being now engaged here as a teacher.
                You<lb/> will perceive from the enclosed what <persName>Dr R.</persName> said to the
                Editor of the<lb/> Asmonean respecting my Grammar; but the latter declined the
                inser-<lb/>tion of it, not because he had the opportunity of giving his own
                opinion<lb/> on it, for that, of course, anyhow, was out of his power, but because
                he would</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>do nothing for nothing; which I am confident will not be the case<lb/> with you; for
                you need not be reminded of <add>אל תמנע טוב מבעליו בהיותו לאל ידך לעשותו</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I remain    Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">your's very respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">S. Newman</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <addressee>Revd I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>The <addressee>Revd I. Leeser</addressee></p>
